<font color="#FF0000">THE &quot;MOVING WALL&quot;</font><br>
<tt>Sun Feb 23 12:10:00 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I,ve not been to the &quot;Wall&quot; in D.C. I have visited the <br>
&quot;Moving Wall&quot; at several different locations. This is about <br>
one of many incidents experienced.<br>
I was talking with several other Vietnam Veterans when a man <br>
approached and ask if I was a soldier. I replied that I had been many<br>
years ago. He ask if his son could meet me. I and the others<br>
were introduced to Jay who had just turned six years old.<br>
He ask me several questions concerning the medals on my <br>
jacket. I ask if he knew any of the names on the &quot;Wall&quot;.<br>
When he answered, &quot;No&quot;, I ask if he would for me to introduce <br>
a friend of mine whose name was there. I got a very <br>
enthusiastic &quot;Yes&quot;. I introduced my friend, <br>
Bobbie Gene Haynes to Jay. Jay stood there for a few minutes,<br>
then ran off. I had returned to the earlier conversation,<br>
when Jay tugged at my sleeve.&quot;Excuse me, but I can't find<br>
your friend's name. I want to give him this note I wrote.&quot;<br>
I took Jay to the panel where Bob's name was. He looked a <br>
second or so, laid the note on the grass, said, &quot;Goodbye&quot;,<br>
then he ran to his Dad. Dad nodded a&quot;thanks&quot;and they walked<br>
away. I knelt to read the note:<br>
Dear Boby,<br>
I met your friend Bill<br>
He is nice<br>
I am sorry you had to die.<br>
Love,<br>
JAY<br>
I could not control my emotions then, as I cannot now.<br>
Someone said earlier that there will be someone at the<br>
&quot;Wall&quot; for you if you need them. It's true.<br>
I'll make to D.C. some day. GOD BLESS YOU, JAY.<br>
'Bye for now.                              
<p><code>-- b2x4x93  (Bill (REB) Marthers) </code><p>


